# VISION

Build an open, AI-native document platform where developers and architects can
structure, evolve, and share project knowledge — with LLMs as first-class
collaborators.

## Problem

Existing formats (PDF, DOCX, Markdown) are either:
- unstructured for machines
- too complex to parse
- not designed for iterative AI collaboration

## Goal

Create a single document format that is:
1. Human-readable in any plain-text editor
2. Semantically structured for LLM consumption
3. Versionable over Git
4. Trivially parseable by tools

## Success Criteria

- A developer can describe a full project in one `.kdoc` file
- An LLM can generate PLAN and TASKS from VISION alone
- The document renders to HTML, slides, and a static site without modification

# CONTEXT

## Target Audience

### Primary Users

Software developers and system architects who need to:
- Document projects from idea to execution
- Collaborate with AI assistants during planning
- Share structured knowledge across teams

### Secondary Users

Technical writers, product managers, researchers using the same
VISION → CONTEXT → STRUCTURE → PLAN → TASKS methodology for non-software work.

## Technical Environment

- Files are plain text (UTF-8), stored in Git
- Tooling runs in Node.js 18+ environments
- VS Code is the primary editing surface (extension included)
- LLM providers: OpenAI, Anthropic, Google (via @kdoc/ai adapter)

## Constraints

- The format must remain human-readable without tooling
- Parser must be implementable in under 500 lines
- No proprietary lock-in — MIT licensed specification

## Competitive Landscape

| Tool      | Structured | AI-native | Plain text | Open |
|-----------|------------|-----------|------------|------|
| Notion    | Partial    | No        | No         | No   |
| Obsidian  | No         | No        | Yes        | No   |
| Confluence| Partial    | No        | No         | No   |
| .kdoc     | Yes        | Yes       | Yes        | Yes  |

# STRUCTURE

## System Architecture

The platform consists of four loosely coupled packages:

```
.kdoc file
    ↓
@kdoc/parser   ← canonical types, parse, validate
    ↓        \
@kdoc/ai      @kdoc/renderer
    ↓              ↓
extension/   ← VS Code UI, AI panel, task management
```

## DECISIONS

- Use a single `.mrcf` file as the project’s source of truth instead of many loosely related markdown files.
- Keep the parser simple and dependency-free so third parties can reimplement it easily.
- Rely on open, plain-text tooling (Git, editors, static HTML) rather than proprietary formats.

## Package: @kdoc/parser

### Responsibilities

- Parse YAML front-matter metadata
- Detect and extract standard sections (VISION, CONTEXT, STRUCTURE, PLAN, TASKS)
- Parse nested subsections (##, ###)
- Extract task checkboxes with optional metadata (owner, priority)
- Extract asset references (images/diagrams)
- Validate documents against 7 rules (V-001 to V-007)

### Key Types

```ts
KDocDocument   // root model
KDocMetadata   // title, version, created, tags, status
KDocSection    // name, content, subsections[], tasks[], assets[]
KDocTask       // description, completed, owner?, priority?
```

### Public API

```ts
parse(source: string): ParseResult
validate(doc: KDocDocument): ValidationResult
resolveAssets(assets, docPath): AssetResolveResult
```

## Package: @kdoc/ai

### Responsibilities

- Provide a unified LLM interface across OpenAI, Anthropic, Google
- Rate limiting with exponential backoff
- Document analysis (consistency checking, completeness)
- Section generation (PLAN from VISION, TASKS from PLAN)
- Diff + Accept/Reject for AI-proposed changes

### Providers

- OpenAI (gpt-4o default)
- Anthropic (claude-sonnet default)
- Google (gemini-pro default)

## Package: @kdoc/renderer

### Responsibilities

- Normalize `KDocDocument` into a format-agnostic `RenderTree`
- Render to full HTML page (with TOC, metadata, theme)
- Generate presentation slide deck (section-to-slide mapping)
- Generate static multi-page documentation site
- Export to HTML, slides, site, ZIP bundle

### Render Pipeline

```
KDocDocument
    ↓  normalize()
RenderTree
    ↓
renderHtml()     → HTML string
generateSlides() → SlideDeck
generateSite()   → Map<filename, HTML>
exportDocument() → ExportResult
```

## Package: extension (VS Code)

### Responsibilities

- Language registration for `.kdoc` files
- Syntax highlighting (TextMate grammar)
- Section folding and outline view
- Sidebar: section list, task explorer, AI panel
- Commands: navigate sections, toggle tasks
- AI panel: presets (Generate PLAN, Generate TASKS, Analyze), section selection

### Editor Keybindings

| Key               | Action                |
|-------------------|-----------------------|
| Ctrl+Alt+Down     | Go to next section    |
| Ctrl+Alt+Up       | Go to previous section|
| Ctrl+Alt+Space    | Toggle task checkbox  |

# PLAN

## Phase 1 — Core Format (Weeks 1–2)

Define the `.kdoc` specification and build the parser.

### Milestones

- `.kdoc` spec published (`docs/kdoc-spec.md`)
- Parser handles all standard sections, subsections, tasks, assets
- Validation engine with 7 rules
- 30+ unit + integration tests passing

## Phase 2 — Editor Integration (Weeks 3–4)

Build VS Code extension with core editing features.

### Milestones

- Language registration and syntax highlighting
- Section outline view and folding
- Task explorer with filtering
- AI panel with mock service

## Phase 3 — AI Integration (Weeks 5–6)

Wire real LLM providers and generation workflows.

### Milestones

- OpenAI, Anthropic, Google providers implemented
- Rate limiting and retry logic
- PLAN generation from VISION
- TASKS generation from PLAN
- Diff + Accept/Reject for AI output

## Phase 4 — Renderer & Export (Weeks 7–8)

Build rendering pipeline and export system.

### Milestones

- HTML renderer with theme, TOC, metadata
- Slide generator with section mapping
- Static site generator (MkDocs-style)
- ZIP export with all assets
- 60+ renderer tests passing

## Phase 5 — Integration & Release (Weeks 9–10)

Wire all four packages together, run end-to-end tests, publish.

### Milestones

- Monorepo workspace setup verified
- End-to-end smoke test: parse → validate → generate → render → export
- VS Code extension published to marketplace
- `kdoc-spec.md` published as open standard (MIT)
- Example project templates available

